Commentary: OUT! TAKEN! New Zealand are nine down now and it's the busy man Josh Hazlewood who takes a good catch in the deep! Bowls it short in length and on the stump line, Tim Southee miscues his pull shot as he is a bit too early on it. It takes the leading edge and hits it aerially looking to clear the fence but the ball doesn't get the distance. Josh Hazlewood runs a few yards ahead from deep square leg and settles underneath it before pouching it safely.

Commentary: OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Another beauty! Nips it away after pitching on the back of a length on off, Matt Henry stays glued on his crease with no real footwork and swings at it but misses. Oh, wait, Australia have gone for a review here for caught behind as Cameron Green who is stationed at gully believes he has heard something! UltraEdge comes up and shows there's a clear spike when the ball passes through the bat. The on-field decision is overturned. The faintest of outside edges and Alex Carey takes another regular grab behind the wickets. Josh Hazlewood finishes up with a sensational 5-fer and New Zealand are bundled out on a paltry 162. And again, the woes for New Zealand in batting continue with this dramatic collapse. And that will be an early TEA on Day 1.
Default_Commentary: 45.2: Josh Hazlewood to Matt Henry, OUT! c Alex Carey b Josh Hazlewood.

Commentary: OUT! LBW! What a moment for the debutant! He gets his first-ever Test wicket in the form of Steven Smith. Ben Sears steams in and serves this full and around off, jags back in sharply, Steven Smith steps across and decides to leave it as the ball thumps his front pads. There is a huge appeal for LBW, and the finger goes up. Smith takes the review. It only needs to clip the wickets and Ball Tracking shows that it is just brushing the off pole and the on-field call remains. Smith is not happy but has to walk back now. New Zealand get a big breakthrough and the lean run for Steven Smith continues in this series.

Commentary: OUT! LBW! A big, confident appeal for LBW, and Matt Henry is literally begging for it but the umpire is unbothered. Tim Southee eventually goes for a review after thinking for an eternity as they only have one review left. This is on the stump line and fuller in length and nips into the batter, Mitchell Marsh plays it across the line of the ball and it pings his pads sneaking through the inside edge. UltraEdge shows that there's no bat involved. Ball Tracker follows up and confirms three reds as the ball clicks the middle and leg stumps. A big, big dismissal as Mitchell Marsh departs on a duck. Matt Henry completes his sensational 5-fer and New Zealand are back in this contest now.

Commentary: OUT! SCREAMER AT GULLY! Is it a bird, or is it a plane? No, it is the flying Glenn Phillips who takes one of the best catches you will ever see. New Zealand needed something special to get rid of Marnus Labuschagne and it is that man Phillips who has provided that with some brilliance on the field. Tim Southee lands this one on a hard length and around off, Marnus Labuschagne stays back and cuts it but does so aerially and wide of gully, Glenn Phillips puts in a Superman dive to his right and grabs a stunner with his outstretched right hand and does well to not ground it while falling down. Only he could have pulled that off on a cricket field and Marnus Labuschagne is in disbelief here. He starts walking back, but the umpires want to check for a fair catch. The replay shows that there is no problem with that and Labushagne has to depart 10 short of his hundred, but he has played a fantastic innings here. Australia eight down now with a lead of 58 runs. THAT WILL ALSO BE LUNCH ON DAY 2!
Default_Commentary: 60.2: Tim Southee to Marnus Labuschagne, OUT! c Glenn Phillips b Tim Southee.
Howout: c Glenn Phillips b Tim Southee

Commentary: OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! An appeal for caught behind from by the Australians but the umpire is unmoved. Pat Cummins after a brief chat with Carey goes upstairs and reviews it and they think there are two noises. Around the wicket and in the channel of off, angling in a bit, Tom Latham rocks back and plays it across the line of the ball creating a gap between the bat and the pad. The ball sneaks through the gates and carries to the keeper. UltraEdge shows that there is indeed a spike on the inside edge when the ball passes through the bat and Tom Latham will have to depart here. An excellent review by Australia. New Zealand lose Tom Latham on 73 and Cummins gets his second.

Commentary: OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Pat Cummins, you beauty! The captain fantastic has done the trick once again for the Aussies. Commentary: OUT! TAKEN! Marnus Labuschagne has just taken an absolute blinder at covers and this match is changing drastically now as Blundell goes too. A dramatic collapse for New Zealand in the last 15 minutes. Cameron Green bowls it on a good length and way outside off, Tom Blundell stays in his crease and goes fishing at it, and slashes it hard but fails to keep it along the ground. The ball rockets to the covers where Marnus Labuschagne stretches his dive to his left and reverse cups it with both hands falling to his left. Green has his hands on his head as he cannot believe that this delivery has got him a wicket. After a couple of angles, the TV umpire confirms that it is a fair catch. A nothing shot from Blundell and now this game is wide open.

Australian skipper finishes off in style and propels his team to clean sweep the series by 2-0, and New Zealand's wait to beat Australia in their own backyard just extends for the time being.
